new file mode 100644
index 00000000..251d5bcc
--- /dev/null
+++ b/wiki/claude-tmux-launcher.md
@@ -0,0 +1,113 @@
+---
+title: Claude tmux launcher & ready detector
+type: reference
+source: lib/hive/claude_launcher.rb, lib/hive/scripts/interactive_claude_wrapper.sh, lib/hive/stop_hook_installer.rb, hive.gemspec, test/unit/claude_launcher_test.rb, test/unit/gemspec_test.rb
+created: 2026-07-11
+updated: 2026-07-11
+tags: [claude, tmux, launcher, packaging, debt]
+---
+
+**TLDR**: `Hive::ClaudeLauncher` launches Claude Code in a tmux session via
+`lib/hive/scripts/interactive_claude_wrapper.sh`, then polls the pane until the
+idle `❯` caret appears. Two coupled defects broke `hive run` on a clean gem
+install with Claude Code 2.1.179: the gemspec did not package the wrapper
+scripts, and the ready detector did not recognize the 2.1.179 boxed prompt.
+Both are fixed and pinned by tests. See [[decisions]], [[testing]], [[gaps]].
+
+## Packaging: `spec.files` must include the shell scripts
+
+`hive.gemspec` builds `spec.files` from an explicit `Dir[...]` list "of only
+the files the runtime actually needs". The `lib/**/*.rb` glob matches Ruby
+source only — the `*.sh` wrappers under `lib/hive/scripts/` are NOT `.rb`, so
+they were silently dropped from the built gem.
+
+On a clean install this is a hard launch failure, not a degraded mode:
+`ClaudeLauncher#wrapper_command` runs `bash <missing-file>`, which exits
+instantly; the tmux session dies before Hive can inspect it, and the launch
+surfaces as `claude_launch_failed` / "can't find pane".
+`Hive::StopHookInstaller` (`lib/hive/scripts/stop_hook.sh`) was omitted the
+same way.
+
+**Fix.** Add a scripts-specific glob `lib/hive/scripts/**/*.sh` to `spec.files`
+(preferred over broadening `lib/**/*`, which would sweep in unrelated non-`.rb`
+files).
+
+**Guard (`test/unit/gemspec_test.rb`).** Three layers, so a future glob edit
+that drops a script is caught:
+
+- `spec.files` unit checks for both known scripts (always-on, fast).
+- An **enumeration-driven** check that scans `lib/**/*.rb` for `scripts/*.sh`
+  string literals (captures `wrapper_command` and `StopHookInstaller::HOOK_PATH`
+  and any future reference) and asserts each resolves to a packaged file — so a
+  newly added script is covered without touching the test. It also asserts the
+  enumeration is non-empty, so a broken regex cannot pass vacuously.
+- A **built-gem** check gated behind `HIVE_GEM_BUILD_TEST=1` that runs
+  `Gem::Package.build` and reads the real `.gem` artifact's file list back;
+  this catches a `spec.files` entry that fails to match any file on disk.
+
+## Ready detector: version-tolerant, no fixed footer offset
+
+The detector keys on the `❯` idle caret — the most stable signal across Claude
+Code TUI revisions. What churns between releases is the caret's POSITION on its
+line and what renders BELOW it. Claude Code 2.1.179 introduced a boxed input:
+`separator / caret / separator / footer`, with the caret as `❯` followed by a
+**non-breaking space (U+00A0)**.
+
+Two failure modes the old detector hit:
+
+- Ruby's `\s` and `String#strip` do NOT cover NBSP, so
+  `CLAUDE_READY_PROMPT_LINE` did not match `❯ ` and the NBSP survived the
+  `.strip` in `claude_ready_prompt?`.
+- The caret is now the 3rd non-blank line from the bottom, but the scan only
+  looked at the last 2 lines (`CLAUDE_PROMPT_TAIL_LINES`), so it never reached
+  the caret. Launch timed out with "claude interactive prompt did not become
+  ready".
+
+**Detector rules now:**
+
+1. **Whitespace tolerance.** `CLAUDE_READY_PROMPT_LINE` and
+   `CLAUDE_MENU_OPTION_LINE` accept ASCII whitespace, NBSP, and any Unicode
+   space separator (`\p{Zs}`), or end-of-line, after a leading `❯` (and before
+   a trailing `❯`).
+2. **Widened window.** `CLAUDE_PROMPT_CONTEXT_LINES` raised 4 → 12 so the whole
+   input box, plus any live permission/trust copy that must veto readiness,
+   stays inside the region. The region is still anchored at the later of the
+   last blank line / last `Claude Code` banner (`current_prompt_text`), which
+   preserves stale-scrollback and stale-trust protections.
+3. **Chrome-below-caret rule (replaces the fixed footer offset).** A caret line
+   is idle when EVERY non-blank line below it, to the bottom of the region, is
+   "chrome": a box-drawing separator (`─│╭╮╰╯├┤┬┴┼`, tolerating a leading `?`
+   render artifact — `CLAUDE_BOX_SEPARATOR_LINE`) or a hint/footer line
+   (`CLAUDE_PROMPT_CHROME_MARKERS`: "for agents", "bypass permissions",
+   "shift+tab to cycle"). Real output below the caret (e.g. "running build
+   step 1") is not chrome, so a stale caret is still rejected — this is what
+   lets the window widen without regressing the "caret above the input box
+   tail" case.
+4. **Negative guards unchanged.** Trust-prompt (`CLAUDE_TRUST_PROMPT_MARKERS`
+   all present), permission (`CLAUDE_PERMISSION_PROMPT_MARKER`), and
+   banner-or-footer presence run ahead of the caret scan. A numbered menu
+   option (`❯ 1.`) is an interactive selection, never the idle prompt.
+
+The chrome glyph/marker sets are version-coupled to Claude Code's current
+rendering, like the banner/footer markers — kept centralized as constants so a
+future Claude change lands in one place.
+
+**Tests.** `test/unit/claude_launcher_test.rb` adds an inline test (NBSP built
+explicitly so editor normalization cannot silently degrade it to a plain space)
+and a committed fixture `test/fixtures/panes/claude_ready_2_1_179.txt` for the
+2.1.179 shape, plus live permission/trust box-layout rejections. All prior
+detector cases keep passing unchanged.
+
+## End-to-end validation caveat: daemon/systemd binary drift
+
+Out of scope for this fix, but recorded so a drifted environment is diagnosed
+rather than misattributed to the detector: the daemon/systemd unit may launch a
+different `hive` binary than the interactive shell (`/usr/bin/hive` vs
+`~/.local/bin/hive`), so an installed-but-stale binary can still fail
+end-to-end even with a green source fix. That drift belongs to the separate
+local-setup / daemon auto-retry work, not here.
+
+## Release vehicle
+
+The expected release vehicle is a `hive-cli` `0.3.3` patch; publishing the gem
+version is a separate release step and out of scope for the source fix.
